A '''resident engineer''' is a construction occupation. It often describes an engineer employed to work from site for the client or the design engineer. The duties include supervision of and issuing of instructions to the contractor and to report regularly to the designer and/or client.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Shah |first1=M. G. |last2=Kale |first2=C. M. |last3=Patki |first3=S. Y. |title=Building Drawing: With an Integrated Approach to Built Environment |date=2002 |publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education |isbn=9780074638767 |page=146 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aRjAcxCRCFsC |language=en}}</ref> The role was common historically and was also defined in the [[Institution of Civil Engineers]] Conditions of Contract and [[FIDIC]] contracts.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Twort |first1=A. C. |last2=Rees |first2=J. G. |title=Civil Engineering: Supervision and Management |date=2012 |publisher=Springer Science & Business Media |isbn=9781461311539 |pages=85-86 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CwTrBwAAQBAJ |language=en}}</ref> It is not a defined role in the commonly used and more modern [[NEC Engineering and Construction Contract]] in which similar roles are named as the client's "project manager" and "supervisor".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Patterson |first1=Richard |title=NEC Engineering and Construction Contract (ECC): the necessary interaction between the supervisor and the project manager |journal=Construction Law Quarterly:Management, Procurement and Law |date=October 2017 |volume=170 |issue=5 |page=225 |url=https://www.neccontract.com/getmedia/ca385188-9110-4f9d-96e6-476f9689124c/ICE-journal-the-interaction-between-Supervisor-and-PM.pdf.aspx |accessdate=19 November 2018}}</ref>
