A '''shadow board''' is a device for organizing a set of tools; the board defines where particular tools should be placed when they are not in use.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FUqbH_nDK-MC&lpg=PT1159&dq=%22shadow%20board%22%20tools&pg=PT1159#v=onepage&q=%22shadow%20board%22%20tools&f=false|title=Tools and Tactics for Operations Managers (Collection)|last=Wilson|first=Randal|last2=Hill|first2=Arthur V.|last3=Glazer|first3=Hillel|date=2013-03-02|publisher=FT Press|isbn=9780133115130|language=en}}</ref> Shadow boards have the outlines of a work station's tools marked on them, allowing operators to identify quickly which tools are in use or missing. The boards are commonly located near the work station where the tools are used. Shadow boards are often used in the manufacturing environment to improve a facility's [[lean six sigma]] capabilities.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TxPSBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA225&dq=%22shadow+board%22+tools+%22six+sigma%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZ9976obbbAhWJAnwKHfU-DUsQ6AEISzAI#v=onepage&q=%22shadow%20board%22%20tools%20%22six%20sigma%22&f=false|title=Reducing Process Costs with Lean, Six Sigma, and Value Engineering Techniques|last=Pries|first=Kim H.|last2=Quigley|first2=Jon M.|date=2012-12-13|publisher=CRC Press|year=|isbn=9781439887264|location=|pages=225|language=en}}</ref>
Shadow boards reduce time spent looking for tools and also reduce losses.{{cn|date=June 2018}} They improve work station safety because tools are replaced safely after use, rather than becoming potential hazards.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
